<home-section>

<h2>Ringggaard Research</h2>

<p>Ringgaard Research ApS is a not-for-profit company that develops and
maintains the SLING system as well as doing research relating to knowledge
management and natural language processing.</p>

<hr>

<table>
<tr>

<td>
  <home-feature>
    <home-icon icon="&#xf121;"></home-icon>
    <h4>SLING</h4>
    <p>SLING is an open source project under an Apache license and all the code is
    available on GitHub. SLING is written mostly in C++ but can be used from Python
    by using the SLING Python API (pysling).</p>
    <p><a href="https://github.com/ringgaard/sling">SLING on GitHub</a></p>
  </home-feature>
</td>

<td>
  <home-feature>
    <home-icon icon="&#xf129;"></home-icon>
    <h4>Knowledge base</h4>
    <p>The SLING knowledge base contains approximately two billion facts about 100
    million entities. Every day a new knowledge base is built from Wikidata as
    well as a number of other information sources.</p>
    <p><a href="/kb/">Browse knowledge base</a></p>
  </home-feature>
</td>

<td>
  <home-feature>
    <home-icon icon="&#xf1c0;"></home-icon>
    <h4>SLINGDB</h4>
    <p>SLINGDB is a lightweight persistent key-value database with a HTTP
    interface. It can be installed independently of the other SLING components
    and is distributed as a standalone Debian package.</p>
    <p><a href="https://github.com/ringgaard/sling/blob/master/doc/guide/slingdb.md">Find Out More</a></p>
  </home-feature>
</td>

<tr>
</table>

</home-section>

